        <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">
         Unit21 took a new approach, one that worked well for eBay\xe2\x80\x99s wide range of products, and in turn, should work for a multitude of use cases beyond financial fraud.
        </p>
        <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">
         Instead of just monitoring the usual financial transaction data points, they told eBay, \xe2\x80\x9cYou can give us
         <em>
          any
         </em>
         data and we\xe2\x80\x99ll treat it like a transaction.\xe2\x80\x9d For example, an analyst at eBay could tag Pok\xc3\xa9mon cards by Pok\xc3\xa9mon. Unit21\xe2\x80\x99s model would learn that a Charizard normally goes for $100, and flag a $1,000 Charizard purchase as anomalous. Or the system might flag a user who purchased too quickly -- if they clicked buy in one second, before having time to review anything, that might mean they didn\xe2\x80\x99t actually care about the item they were buying.
        </p>
